	            	                <li class="dsq-comment dsq-clearfix" data-dsq-comment-id="1512043306" id="dsq-comment-1512043306">
	                    <div class="dsq-avatar dsq-tt">
	                        <a href="https://disqus.com/by/weaverryan/">
	                            	                                <img alt="" src="http://a.disquscdn.com/uploads/users/32/6480/avatar92.jpg?1482356913">
	                            	                        </a>
	                    </div>
	                    <div class="dsq-comment-body" id="dsq-comment-body-1512043306">
	                        <div class="dsq-comment-header">
	                            <span class="dsq-comment-date">2014-07-30</span>
	                            <span class="dsq-commenter-name">weaverryan</span>
	                        </div>

	                        <div id="dsq-comment-message-1512043306" class="dsq-comment-message">
	                            <div id="dsq-comment-text-1512043306" class="dsq-comment-text">
	                                <p>Hi Joe!</p><p>I'm glad you like it, and *such* a good question!</p><p>So, let's look at what encodePassword is actually doing:</p><p>1) It accesses Symfony's container object (that one magic object that holds all other important objects in the system (check out: <a href="http://disq.us/url?url=http%3A%2F%2Fknpuniversity.com%2Fscreencast%2Fsymfony2-ep1%2Fcontroller%23symfony-services%29%3A_5WnjP_jdPqT1HrzSjy4uAYcfsM&amp;cuid=1175718" rel="nofollow noopener">http://knpuniversity.com/scree...</a></p><p>2) It uses this container object and asks it for the "security.encoder_factory" service. This returns the object that's known by this name.</p><p>3) We use the "security.encoder_factory" object</p><p>So, for (1), we need to know where this all-important container object lives. Symfony is made so that in a controller, you can just say $this-&gt;container. But that *only* works in a controller. But, in this script - if you look near the middle of the file (before we start coding), you'll see that we've booted Symfony and I've grabbed the container and set it as a $container variable. So, if you just remove the encodePassword function and write everything inline with your user-creation, all you need is:</p><p></p><pre><code><br>$user = new User();<br><br>// ...<br>$encoder = $container-&gt;get('security.encoder_factory')<br>-&gt;getEncoder($user);<br><br>$encodedPassword = $encoder-&gt;encodePassword('password', $user-&gt;getSalt());<br>$user-&gt;setPassword($encodedPassword);<br></code></pre><p></p><p>So the trick is always to figure out where this container object is. If you can find it, you can get any object you want.</p><p>Cheers!</p>
	                            </div>
	                        </div>
	                    </div>
	                </li>
